      <div class="msgContentFrame">It's hard to limit top improvements to just 3 lol. I know much of this has been said before, so my apologies, but I've been playing this now for a month, so I've had a fair amount of time to observe and digest. <br /> <br />There were so many features in ffxi that we took for granted, that simplified the mechanics of the game, allowing us to enjoy the game content, rather than be caught up in executing mechanics.  <br /> <br />1. Auction House and Delivery Box - I honestly don't know why SE is so resistant to this, and I've never understood why some feel this promotes RMT activity. No matter what the system, there will always be RMT's. They adjust better than regular players, regardless. AH was the backbone of ffxi economic standards. It established an economic worth that coincided with the difficulty of obtaining the item. With retainers, item X in bazaar 1 is 50K, in another unrelated ward, same item 5K. WTF let supply/demand dictate an established price. I spend, sometimes, 5 hours searching each and every retainer for an item that with an AH would take 30 seconds. 90% of the retainers are in the wrong market ward, are seeking/selling shards/crystals, selling junk I wouldn't even bother npc'g. I've seen more gridania nuts and marmot pelts enough to last a lifetime already. Why should I be subjected to this?  <br /> <br />Retainers do nothing more than take up valuable system resources and players time. How many times have you tele'd to a market ward to see nothing but names coming out of the floor? How many times have you moved your charcter an inch to see 50 more retainers pop? I mean OMG &gt;&lt; Which ones did I check? I don't know. <br /> <br />SE had it so right in ffxi with an AH concept, and so so so wrong with retainers. Just bite the bullet and fix the biggest design bust in the game, please. <br /> <br />2. Macros - I played ffxi 6 years on a PS2, unfortunately. I cried every day about lag, black screen, limited macro capabilities vs. PC players and windower. However, compared to even those limited PS2 macro capabilities, ffxiv is the most hideously designed macro system I could have imagined.  I know they're promising to fix some of this, but really, regardless of simplification in setting up with copy/paste, etc. Why does it take 15 seconds for a gear swap/equip action macro to execute? I mean seriously, windower had it right, no limitations of lines, immediate execution, etc. Right now, you equip your R.ear, the mob hits you for 100 damage, you equip your L.wrist, the mob crits you for 220 damage, you equip your main, the mobs hits you for 150 damage, you equip fire in action 3 slot, the mob hits you for 140 damage, you're incapacitated, do you wish to return? I mean seriously &gt;&lt; <br /> <br />3. Communications - Despite having played ffxi for years, I was absolutly lost in ffxiv when I first started. I'd get a /tell and go to /reply and nothing. Even now that I understand this, hit the space bar first. Why? To even use /r you need have /t that player first, and yay, two name convention, joy. Even after playing a month now, I can't tell you how many times I go to initiate chat and end up executing some keyboard command because I didn't hit space bar first. What about a chat log where I can look at says, tells, party, ls chat only? Ffxi had that. Instead, no matter where I go I have to sort thru 9484757 lines of synthing data. Yes I suppose I could filter out alot of that, but still. Also to play this game today, I need a keyboard, a game pad, and yes, a mouse &gt;&lt;  the only way I know how to scroll back thru the text is with a mouse. I have 2 hands only, I never had to do this with ffxi. I could do it with my game pad. Guys, you had it right in ffxi, why so cumbersome now? <br /> <br />4. Text - color, size, background. Purple text, no background, so tiny I have to squint to see it from more than 5' away - REALLY? <br /> <br />- Computer to play this game - $2200 <br />- 47&quot; HD TV - $1500 <br />- Leather recliner that I played ffxi from for years, - $800 <br />- Remote blue tooth keyboard, mouse, and wireless gamepad - $250 <br />- Having to sit on the floor directly in front of the TV to see the print priceless &gt;&lt; <br /> <br />Never had this problem with ffxi - just kick back in the recliner and have fun. I swear I'm almost cripple from having to sit on the floor in front of the TV to see the game. I can see where everything is ok for those that sit at a PC monitor to play this game, but really, I don't want to have to do that. What about when this comes out for PS3 players? You think they're going to want to have to sit right on top of their TV's to effectively play this game?  <br /> <br />5. Need some sort of relief for gear damage. Not sure exactly what. I sneeze sometimes and I get gear damage. You know, having the repair npc fix stuff to 75% for entry level gear is ok, I suppose. But the cost jumps from next to nothing to 9385767 gil to repair your level 15 staff. Really? So the solution - stand there and /sh for someone to fix your gear, or level every damn craft in the game so you can repair your own - a little severe, wouldn't you say? At some point down the road, there will be no economic stimulus, because everyone in the game will have leveled every craft. So tell me, who's going to need what from whom? lol I'm ok with the concept, to some degree, but this clearly needs to be refined, somehow. <br /> <br />6. It would be nice if SP and XP were even remotely connected to mob difficulty. Today I can fight a orange/red mob and get 50 SP, then turn around and fight a blue and get 175 - hmmm. So, should I bother leveling on appropriate mobs when there's no guarantee of SP reward? Take serious gear damage as they're bashing my head in, and get 25 SP, or just annhilate whatever I come across and hope for an equal reward?  <br /> <br />I'll stop here, but the list continues. I know that SE is working to correct so many of the game's shortcomings, which is encouraging, but seriously, they had so much of it right in ffxi - why reinvent the wheel? It's round and it rolls, man - it was a good thing.</div>
