      <div class="msgContentFrame">1. Mini games <br />Questing, killing monsters and crafting items are all wonderful ways to spend your time in Eorzea, but even the most devoted player needs a diversion from time to time. Add in simple card games, races, or perhaps even the occasional stage show (The Mumor thing on FFXI was a missed opportunity for a player-wowing FMV event in my opinion). Simple things like this keep the game entertaining even after a long grind. <br /> <br />2. Summoners <br />Okay, we all know they're coming eventually but I couldn't go without mentioning one of the most beloved of Final Fantasy features, the summons. I love summons, though I confess I wasn't amazingly keen on the Summoner class given to us in FFXI. With all-powerful mystical beings at your beck and call, what's not to like about wielding their strength? That being said, summons need to be as impressive as their forebears. <br /> <br />Go back to a time before FFXI and Summons were deadly forces of nature, tearing up the landscape and even destroying entire planets to destroy your foes. Granted, such power would be unwieldy in an MMO, and the repair bill from Ul'dah's finance minister would be in the billions. All the same, make them strong enough to be known for it but flexible enough to use in parties without putting Conjurers out of a job. <br /> <br />3. Crafting quality <br />Make it do something! Please. The first logical thought when dealing with the quality aspect of an item you are crafting is that it somehow guarantees you a shot at a +1 item if you manage to push the quality high enough. This is not so, which is rather frustrating and leaves many wondering why you should bother using 'Bold synthesis' on a non-leve craft. <br /> <br />It needn't be easy, just make it plain to see how well the synthesis is going. A few examples, if you'll humour me. <br /> <br />0-100% quality: 0% chance of HQ item <br />101-200% quality: 10% chance of HQ item <br />201-300% quality: 50% chance of HQ item <br />400+ quality: HQ item guaranteed <br /> <br />Obviously I just threw some figures in there as an example. SE probably knows how to balance these things far better than I do. But after a certain degree of quality, high quality goods should be assured, not merely a chance. After all, if it's got double the normal quality, surely it's twice the value! <br /> <br />Those are my thoughts anyway.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><a href="HTTP://lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/top?cicuid=5524435" rel="external nofollow" title="lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/top?cicuid=5524435"><img src="http://common.zam.com/xivsigs/1814124.png" alt="Signature Image" border="0" /></a></div></div>
