      <div class="msgContentFrame">1. Make the developers play, both solo and party, for a set number of hours a week. Until they actually start gaming a bit, they'll never actually -get- what the playerbase is saying. <br /> <br />2. Fix the UI lag. I've logged in like three times in the last month and a half - just long enough to check out the leves and get annoyed by how clunky and sluggish the UI is. The UI lag alone is the major thing that keeps me from logging in. My interest in FFXIV is almost gone. I've stopped checking these boards and I no longer care about deleting the extra character I made. <br /> <br />For those of you who say &quot;Well, fine. GTFO&quot; all I can say is that's incredibly shortsighted. For a MMO to thrive, you -need- more players. You need a constant influx of new people. Losing this many people while the monthly fees have been waived is really disheartening and may be an obstacle FFXIV will never recover from if they don't get a move on it. <br /> <br />It doesn't matter how novel and avant-garde your ideas are if no one is there to appreciate them. <br /> <br />3. More updates addressing smaller issues. Get a move on it, SE. You need to get into panic mode. Both the rate of updates and some of the changes you're making to the game, while welcome, just aren't -enough-. You need to devote more manpower to this if you even hope to dig yourself out of this hole you've gotten into. <br /> <br />Good luck. I -want- to play this game. I want FFXIV to succeed. I would very much like to, in a few years, look back at this launch with a wry smile and say &quot;I'm glad SE got it together.&quot;<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><span class="sm">Looking for a linkshell active during Australian/East Asian hours? Drop me a PM.^^</span> <br /> <br /><span class="sm">fun &gt; {Experience Points}</span></div></div>
