      </div>
      <div class="msgContentFrame">Yes, the lack of an AH and working UI sucks, but that's fixable fairly easily. That's tweaking the game mechanics and fixing the UI. Any coder with a can of cola can do that.  <br /> <br />The main isse I have with FFXIV is the near complete lack of story content, NPC life, world elements etc.  <br /> <br /><b>The levequest system</b> is actually the main thing I would change. It is simply neither fun nor engaging to do repeatable quests from day one. You never meet the characters that populate the FFXIV world - you get the quest through an innkeeper who says &quot;this is for Bob&quot;. Okay, whatever, I usually never get to meet Bob, I just run from the innkeeper to a bloody stone, do the quest and hand it in. <b>It feels like a chore and not an adventure</b>. We know that SE can write good stories - why don't they? Also, the levequest structure promotes grinding. When you can repeat quests efficiently again and again in a known location for 10 levels, you have no real reason to move around and explore the world.  <br /> <br />Which bring me to my second main issue with FFXIV <b>- the world.</b> It just seems bland and empty. No NPCs want to talk to you (cause the innkeeper handles the quests). The only times when you interact with any NPC is when you need to buy or sell anything. There is no sound from the market street, no chatter in the plaza, the image is silent and still. The only ones moving are PCs and let's be honest - their numbers are dwindling. Running around in FFXIV is like running around in an empty gaming world with basically no NPC interaction. I really really miss <b>speech bubbles</b>. Seriously, (optional) bubbles is such an easy way to make a world feel that much more alive. You can tell by sight where people are chatting, you can listen in on their conversations, you can say something to the people around you and they will &quot;hear&quot; you without having to scroll trhough their tiny flooded chat prompt. The cities are nicely designed, but they provide no sense of &quot;life&quot; and the camps are bad jokes. Oh, how I miss the small settlements that litter the countryside of Azeroth...  <br /> <br />And, while I do appreciate some aspects of the <b>&quot;one char can do all stuff&quot;-thing</b>, it gets boring really fast that all classes are exactly the same. Come on, give the huge mammoth guys a strenght bonus and the gnomes a magic bonus or something, and give the catgirls the ability to jump a little bit higher than the rest. When the difference is only cosmetic and everyone is basically playing the exact same character, it gets old really really fast. And if I want to experience the starting story of Limsa with a Lalafel fisherman... guess what? I have to pay extra.  <br /> <br />Which brings me to my final point: <b>cut out the crap with characters and bank-space costing extra</b>. One character (minimum) should be included with the @#%^ing basic subscription - what use is a game without a character? None. That makes the basic monthly fee a scam. You should be able to gain all the bank-space you need by gathering in-game resources - you shouldn't need to put in real world money to get more space. Oh, and how about adding an actual BANK in the cities? <div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>Journal of the Kitty - the adventures of Vivacia Yuuki of the Rabanastre world <br /><a href="http://ffxivjournal.blogspot.com/" title="http://ffxivjournal.blogspot.com/" rel="external nofollow">http://ffxivjournal.blogspot.com/</a></div></div>
