      <div class="msgContentFrame">The random SP gain system is gone and it should stay gone forever. The simple fact is that SE has chosen, stupidly, to base main storyline progression solely on rank. This is a far cry from XI's skillup system since instead of punishing inattention to your job's pertinent skills, it's now the only way to progress through not only the story, but your ability list. SP gain needs to stay static, but it also needs to be made reasonable again. <br /> <br />That said, my three: <br /> <br />1) <b>Auction House</b>. No brainer. Using retainers as the sole basis for the economy is stupid. Kudos for trying to think outside the box but retainers never should've made it through beta. <br /> <br />2) <b>Crafting and Gathering</b>. Different types of synthesis should have noticeable, consistent results (not to be confused with success or failure). Right now, crafting makes no actual sense - the options are there but it's not worth doing anything but Standard Synthesis. The orb changes color but there's no perceptible difference in the results. This got messed up somehow and it needs to be reviewed. Gathering - where you choose to gather (on the slider, not the actual node) should consistently yield certain types of rewards. For example, gathering high in a tree has a greater chance for branches; gathering lower, for logs. I haven't noticed any consistency like this in my myriad gathering adventures. <br /> <br />3) <b>Levequests</b>. They're boring, plain and simple. Really great idea, really crappy implementation. It was wonderful to see them go hand-in-hand so well with leveling at first, but then you notice there's no depth - it's just gussied-up grinding. I'm not saying they should be anything else besides that, but right now they just aren't trying with the gussying. The NM leves will be a welcome change and SE should keep expanding the <b>types</b> of leves there are. Not just the words on the quest window. <br /> <br />I would happily come back and play if these things changed. In my opinion, they are the biggest obstacles in the way, but even their implementation would only take FFXIV from &quot;unplayable&quot; to &quot;basically functional.&quot; SE has a long way to go.</div>
